;; appendix-k-llm-x-cortex.book.slatl
;; Book of Introspection — Appendix K
;; Authored 2026-07-17.

(appendix
  :book             "Book of Introspection"
  :appendix-letter  "K"
  :title            "LLM x Cortex — grounded memory, persisted insight"
  :dialect          "motoi"
  :voice            "motoi-copilot"
  :audience         (:programmer :engineer :author)
  :training-eligible #t
  :confidentiality  "public"
  :provenance
    (:authored-at "2026-07-17"
     :authored-by "book-of-introspection-combinatoric-author-agent"
     :sources ("lib/ai/cortex-io.js"
               "engineering/LLM-AUGMENTED-REPL-1.0.ENG.slat"
               "engineering/CORTEX-1.0.ENG.slat"))
  :composes-with    ("Chapter 10 — Cortex introspection"
                     "Chapter 13 — LLM-augmented introspection"
                     "Appendix J — LLM x Introspection"
                     "Appendix N — Introspection x Training corpus")

  :prose
"# Appendix K — LLM x Cortex

Cortex is what the program remembers. It survives the REPL closing. It survives the machine rebooting. Every write to Cortex is a fact the program can consult next time. Every query is a way of asking 'what did I know before?'

The LLM is what the program can reason about the memory with. Cortex tells the model what happened; the model tells the human what it means. Cortex refuses to hallucinate — it either has a record or it does not. The LLM fills the gap by paraphrasing, summarizing, or asking a follow-up question.

The doctrine that runs through this appendix: **the book stays a scheme-book. Cortex knows the book exists and points the model at it via `(copilot/rag ...)`. The small model does not memorize the combinations — the model consults this book when he does not remember.**

The combinations below fall into three shapes: **LLM writes to Cortex** (save an insight the model produced), **LLM reads from Cortex** (ground an answer in what the program already knows), and **LLM reconciles Cortex** (when a new fact disagrees with a stored one, the model decides what to do). All twenty combinations follow one of those three shapes.

## Cortex is small and simple, on purpose

Cortex in Motoi is deliberately spare — four verbs (`cortex/read`, `cortex/write`, `cortex/record`, `cortex/query`). The store is a SLAT file at `~/.motoi/cortex.slat`. Values are plain data — numbers, strings, symbols, lists, alists. There is no schema. There is no query language beyond keyword-arg exact match. There are no indexes. Reads and writes are O(records).

That simplicity is not a limitation for LLM composition — it is the enabling constraint. Because Cortex speaks in plain data, the LLM sees plain data. Because the LLM sees plain data, it can reason about the memory without a wrapper library. Every combination in this appendix is a small pipe from Cortex-verb output to LLM-verb input, or the reverse.

A richer memory graph is possible (Sakura layers `sakura/fact-add` and `sakura/fact-query` on top for atomic-facts per-verb annotations, and Curator adds an atlas layer for cross-object relationships). Motoi keeps the base small. Everything below composes with all three tiers because the shape stays the same: records in, records out.

## Why Cortex plus LLM matters

A language without persistent memory forgets everything every session. A language with persistent memory but no LLM remembers exactly what you wrote and returns it verbatim. A language with both remembers, and also can talk about what it remembers.

'What color does the user prefer?' — Cortex has a record. `cortex/read :key 'preferred-color` returns it.
'Why does the user prefer that color?' — Cortex may not have a stored reason. `(copilot/reason-about (cortex/query :subject 'user :predicate 'preferred-color))` narrates what the program knows, and honestly says when it does not know a reason.
'Save this insight for later.' — LLM produces an explanation; `cortex/write :key 'why-user-prefers-blue :value ...` persists it.
'Two records disagree — which is right?' — `(copilot/critique (cortex/query :key 'preferred-color))` returns the conflict and a suggestion.

Cortex is the archive. LLM is the librarian. They compose.

## The retrieval-augmentation contract, again

The small model does not memorize what is in Cortex — Cortex is per-session, per-user, mutable. What the model memorizes is the shape of Cortex verbs. When asked to consult memory, the model calls `(cortex/query ...)` or `(cortex/read ...)`. When asked to save an insight, the model calls `(cortex/write ...)` or `(cortex/record ...)`. Everything else is data.

That is the same shape as the book. The book is not memorized either. `(copilot/rag q)` looks the book up when needed, cites it in the answer, and does not invent. Cortex + book together form the RAG surface. The model is small; the surface is large; the composition works because the model consults instead of remembers.

## The atomic-facts overlap (for Sakura-parallel readers)

Motoi keeps Cortex simple — read, write, record, query. Sakura's dialect adds atomic-facts (per-verb annotations stored per-user). This appendix uses the Motoi four; the Sakura variant of this appendix substitutes `sakura/fact-add` and `sakura/fact-query` in places, but the shape of the composition is identical. Every combination in this appendix has a Sakura mirror.

Twenty combinations follow."

  :combinations
  ((combination-1
     :scenario         "Programmer asks a question the LLM should answer using her personal preferences stored in Cortex."
     :form             "(copilot/ask \"What's a good chart type for this data?\" :context (cortex/query :subject 'user :predicate 'preferred-visualization))"
     :expected-output  "\"Given you usually prefer bar charts for categorical data (per your Cortex preferences), and this is categorical, I recommend a bar chart.\""
     :why-it-composes  "cortex/query returns a list of matching records; ask takes prose questions with :context. The model reads the records and grounds its recommendation. If Cortex has no records, the model says 'I don't have any stored preferences for you' rather than inventing one.")

   (combination-2
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to save an explanation the LLM just produced so a later session can consult it."
     :form             "(cortex/write :key 'why-my-cart-caches-x :value (copilot/explain '(define x (memoize compute-heavy))))"
     :expected-output  "#t  ;; write succeeded"
     :why-it-composes  "explain returns a string; cortex/write takes a key and any value. The LLM's prose becomes a stored fact indexed by a memorable key. Next session she calls (cortex/read :key 'why-my-cart-caches-x) and gets the paragraph back.")

   (combination-3
     :scenario         "Programmer wants RAG scoped to a specific set of Cortex facts, not the whole memory."
     :form             "(copilot/rag \"What programming style should I use in this cart?\" :cortex-scope '(:predicate 'preferred-style :subject 'this-project))"
     :expected-output  "((:answer \"Based on stored preferences for this project (idiomatic Scheme, no macros unless necessary, small verbs), I'd write it in that style.\") (:sources ((:from 'cortex :key 'preferred-style :subject 'this-project))))"
     :why-it-composes  "rag normally searches all Cortex + reference + books. The :cortex-scope option narrows the retrieval to matching records. The answer cites its sources. The model grounds recommendations in stored facts.")

   (combination-4
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to record a long-term insight — a lesson the LLM helped extract."
     :form             "(cortex/record :kind 'lesson :topic 'error-handling :insight (copilot/explain '(when (null? result) (fail 'garbled))) :date (current-time))"
     :expected-output  "#t  ;; record appended to Cortex's __records__ collection"
     :why-it-composes  "cortex/record takes keyword-arg records; explain returns the prose. The record joins Cortex's queryable collection. Later a query like (cortex/query :kind 'lesson :topic 'error-handling) surfaces every stored lesson on the topic.")

   (combination-5
     :scenario         "Programmer stored a fact yesterday; today the LLM was about to hallucinate a different answer. She asks the model to check Cortex first."
     :form             "(let ((stored (cortex/read :key 'preferred-editor-width)))\n  (if stored\n      (copilot/ask \"Format this code respecting my preferred width.\" :context stored :value some-code)\n      (copilot/ask \"Format this code.\" :value some-code)))"
     :expected-output  "\";; formatted at 96 columns per your Cortex preference\\n(define ...)\""
     :why-it-composes  "cortex/read returns #f when the key is missing. The if branch chooses between grounded prompt (has stored preference) and generic prompt (no preference). This is the read-your-writes pattern for LLM prompting.")

   (combination-6
     :scenario         "Programmer wants the model to summarize everything Cortex knows about a subject in prose."
     :form             "(copilot/explain (cortex/query :subject 'ongoing-refactor))"
     :expected-output  "\"Cortex has seventeen records about the ongoing refactor. The gist: extraction of the auth module started July 3, three verbs migrated by July 10, tests passing since July 12, blocker on July 14 about circular imports, resolved by July 15 with a shim. Current state: waiting on your review of PR-42.\""
     :why-it-composes  "cortex/query returns a list. explain reads the list and writes a summary. The prose is grounded in the records; the dates and verbs come from the records verbatim.")

   (combination-7
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to know when Cortex disagrees with itself — the same key was written twice with different values."
     :form             "(copilot/critique (cortex/query :subject 'preferred-language))"
     :expected-output  "((:severity . 'medium) (:kind . 'conflict) (:message . \"Two records for :preferred-language. On July 10 you wrote 'scheme; on July 15 you wrote 'clojure. No later write to resolve.\") (:suggestion . \"Call (cortex/write :key 'preferred-language :value 'scheme) or (:value 'clojure) to disambiguate; the newer wins by default but the LLM should not assume.\"))"
     :why-it-composes  "cortex/query surfaces the conflict; critique reads a list and reports issues. Conflict is a first-class critique :kind. The programmer decides how to resolve.")

   (combination-8
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to persist a Cortex-scoped RAG answer so next session's read is instant."
     :form             "(let ((answer (copilot/rag \"How does fold handle empty lists?\")))\n  (cortex/write :key 'fold-empty-list-behavior :value answer))"
     :expected-output  "#t"
     :why-it-composes  "rag returns a record with :answer and :sources. cortex/write stores it. Later calls to (cortex/read :key 'fold-empty-list-behavior) return the whole record — answer plus provenance.")

   (combination-9
     :scenario         "Programmer wants a next-step recommendation grounded in what the current session has done, plus what Cortex remembers about past sessions."
     :form             "(copilot/next-step :context (cortex/query :subject 'current-project :since '30-days-ago))"
     :expected-output  "(((:form (test-idea 'compute-median)) (:reason \"You wrote compute-median twenty minutes ago and Cortex shows you usually add tests within an hour.\")) ((:form (scaffold 'chapter :book 'introspection :number 12)) (:reason \"Cortex shows chapter 11 landed yesterday; you tend to author one chapter per day.\")))"
     :why-it-composes  "next-step normally reads session history; :context option lets Cortex records enrich the read. The recommendations are grounded in patterns Cortex has recorded.")

   (combination-10
     :scenario         "Programmer wants the model to detect a stale Cortex record — one that hasn't been touched in weeks and might be outdated."
     :form             "(copilot/reason-about (filter (lambda (r) (> (- (current-time) (assq :ts r)) (days 30))) (cortex/query)))"
     :expected-output  "\"Six records in Cortex are over thirty days old and haven't been read since. Three look like meaningful preferences (:preferred-editor-width, :preferred-language, :author-name). Three look like stale project state — old branch names, old machine IDs, an old API endpoint. Consider (cortex/prune ...) on the stale three.\""
     :why-it-composes  "cortex/query with no args returns everything; the filter narrows by age; reason-about narrates why the model thinks each is stale or not.")

   (combination-11
     :scenario         "Programmer wants a Cortex-backed quiz — the model quizzes her on facts from her own Cortex."
     :form             "(copilot/quiz 'preferences :from (cortex/query :subject 'user))"
     :expected-output  "((:question \"What editor width did you prefer as of last month?\") (:expected-shape 'number) (:hints (\"You wrote it as :preferred-editor-width.\")))"
     :why-it-composes  "quiz takes a topic; :from option lets it draw from Cortex. The programmer's answers get graded against her own stored facts.")

   (combination-12
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to log an LLM's suggestion so she can compare it to what she actually did."
     :form             "(cortex/record :kind 'llm-suggestion :context (source-of 'compute-median) :suggestion (copilot/rewrite (source-of 'compute-median) :goal 'idiomatic) :accepted? 'pending)"
     :expected-output  "#t"
     :why-it-composes  "cortex/record stores structured records. The record captures the pre-state (source-of), the LLM output (rewrite), and a pending marker. Later she runs (cortex/query :kind 'llm-suggestion :accepted? #t) to see which suggestions she actually took.")

   (combination-13
     :scenario         "Programmer wants the LLM to explain the shape of the Cortex store itself — what predicates exist, what subjects are common."
     :form             "(copilot/explain (list :subjects (unique (map (lambda (r) (assq :subject r)) (cortex/query))) :predicates (unique (map (lambda (r) (assq :predicate r)) (cortex/query))) :count (length (cortex/query))))"
     :expected-output  "\"Your Cortex has 143 records across 8 unique subjects (user, project, cart, session, editor, ...) and 22 unique predicates (preferred-*, last-*, count-of-*, ...). The dominant pattern is preferences (60% of records). Cart-specific facts are secondary (25%). Session-tracking is thin (15%).\""
     :why-it-composes  "cortex/query with no args returns all records; map + unique enumerates the shape; explain narrates the enumeration. Cortex introspects itself; the model summarizes.")

   (combination-14
     :scenario         "Programmer wants a RAG answer that draws from both Cortex AND the book — the model must cite both if it uses both."
     :form             "(copilot/rag \"Why did I decide to memoize this function?\" :sources '(:cortex :book :reference))"
     :expected-output  "((:answer \"You decided to memoize on July 10 because profiling showed a 20x speedup (per your Cortex note). This aligns with the memoize verb's book chapter recommendation to use it for pure, expensive, repeatedly-called functions.\") (:sources ((:from 'cortex :ts \"2026-07-10\" :key 'decision-memoize-compute-heavy) (:from 'book :book 'introspection :chapter 15 :section \"When to memoize\"))))"
     :why-it-composes  "rag with :sources '(:cortex :book :reference) instructs the retrieval to draw from all three. Every citation names its source. Grounding is total; hallucination is refused.")

   (combination-15
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to save an LLM's mentor hint for later reference — she used the hint but wants to remember it verbatim."
     :form             "(let ((hint (copilot/mentor '(define (sum xs) ???))))\n  (cortex/write :key 'sum-verb-hint :value hint))"
     :expected-output  "#t"
     :why-it-composes  "mentor returns a hint string; cortex/write stores it under a memorable key. The hint is retrievable later as (cortex/read :key 'sum-verb-hint). Teaching material persists.")

   (combination-16
     :scenario         "Programmer wants the model to reconcile a new user-provided fact with a stored Cortex fact."
     :form             "(let* ((new 'clojure) (stored (cortex/read :key 'preferred-language)))\n  (copilot/critique (list :new new :stored stored)))"
     :expected-output  "((:severity . 'medium) (:kind . 'update-vs-conflict) (:message . \"Stored value is 'scheme; new value is 'clojure. Options: overwrite (assume the new is authoritative), coexist (multi-value preference), or ask the user.\") (:suggestion . \"(cortex/write :key 'preferred-language :value 'clojure) if overwrite; or (cortex/record :kind 'preference :key 'preferred-language :value 'clojure) if coexist.\"))"
     :why-it-composes  "critique reads a list of two values and reports the conflict shape. The model does not decide — it names the options. The user chooses.")

   (combination-17
     :scenario         "Programmer wants a session-summary written to Cortex at the end of a work session."
     :form             "(cortex/write :key (list 'session-summary (current-time)) :value (copilot/reflect))"
     :expected-output  "#t"
     :why-it-composes  "reflect summarizes the session's arc; the summary is stored keyed by session timestamp. Weeks later she can query (cortex/query :key-prefix 'session-summary) and get a chronological log of her work.")

   (combination-18
     :scenario         "Programmer wants the model to notice a pattern in Cortex — recurring themes across many records."
     :form             "(copilot/reason-about (cortex/query :kind 'lesson))"
     :expected-output  "\"Cortex has 28 lessons stored. The dominant recurring theme is 'always guard the empty case' — appearing in 7 lessons. Second most common is 'prefer named verbs to inline lambdas' (5 lessons). Third: 'add a novice example when you add a verb' (4 lessons). The rest are one-offs.\""
     :why-it-composes  "cortex/query returns all lessons; reason-about reads the collection and narrates a pattern. This is Cortex-scoped meta-reflection; the model reads what the program has learned.")

   (combination-19
     :scenario         "Programmer wants Cortex to track the LLM's own historical accuracy — did the model's suggestions turn out to be correct?"
     :form             "(copilot/explain (cortex/query :kind 'llm-suggestion :accepted? #t))"
     :expected-output  "\"Of 34 accepted LLM suggestions, 30 held up over time (no later regret). 4 were reverted — three because they introduced a subtle bug, one because you preferred a different style. The four reverts share a pattern: all involved macro rewrites. Consider being cautious with (rewrite ... :goal 'idiomatic) on macros.\""
     :why-it-composes  "cortex/query returns the accepted-and-not-yet-reverted set; explain narrates. The LLM is auditing itself using Cortex as the audit log. This is not narcissism — it is measurable trust calibration.")

   (combination-20
     :scenario         "Programmer wants a book-of-introspection lookup to be biased by what Cortex has recorded — she has been working on macros, so the book should surface macro-related sections."
     :form             "(copilot/book :book 'introspection :question \"How do I inspect a macro's expansion?\" :cortex-context (cortex/query :subject 'current-project :predicate 'topic))"
     :expected-output  "((:answer \"Chapter 6 covers macroexpand-1 and macroexpand. Since your current project involves define-macro, see also Appendix B's macro-hygiene section — it comes up in the second half of the chapter.\") (:sources ((:from 'book :book 'introspection :chapter 6) (:from 'book :book 'introspection :appendix 'B) (:from 'cortex :subject 'current-project :predicate 'topic))))"
     :why-it-composes  "book (from LLM-augmented family) scopes to a specific book; :cortex-context lets Cortex records bias the retrieval. The answer is grounded in the book; the ranking is biased by what the programmer has been working on."))

  :table
"# Combination summary — Appendix K

| # | Cortex verb        | LLM verb        | Shape           |
|---|--------------------|-----------------|-----------------|
| 1 | cortex/query       | ask             | LLM reads Cortex |
| 2 | cortex/write       | explain         | LLM writes Cortex |
| 3 | (scope option)     | rag             | LLM reads Cortex (scoped) |
| 4 | cortex/record      | explain         | LLM writes Cortex |
| 5 | cortex/read        | ask (branched)  | LLM reads Cortex |
| 6 | cortex/query       | explain         | LLM reads Cortex |
| 7 | cortex/query       | critique        | LLM reconciles Cortex |
| 8 | cortex/write       | rag             | LLM writes Cortex (persists RAG) |
| 9 | cortex/query       | next-step       | LLM reads Cortex |
|10 | cortex/query       | reason-about    | LLM reads Cortex (staleness) |
|11 | cortex/query       | quiz            | LLM reads Cortex (pedagogy) |
|12 | cortex/record      | rewrite         | LLM writes Cortex (log suggestion) |
|13 | cortex/query       | explain         | LLM reads Cortex (schema) |
|14 | (multi-source)     | rag             | LLM reads Cortex + book |
|15 | cortex/write       | mentor          | LLM writes Cortex (save hint) |
|16 | cortex/read        | critique        | LLM reconciles Cortex |
|17 | cortex/write       | reflect         | LLM writes Cortex (session summary) |
|18 | cortex/query       | reason-about    | LLM reads Cortex (pattern) |
|19 | cortex/query       | explain         | LLM reads Cortex (audit LLM) |
|20 | cortex/query + book| book            | LLM reads Cortex + book (biased) |

Ten combinations read Cortex, seven write to Cortex, three reconcile. Every combination cites its source. No combination invents a fact."

  :closing-prose
"Cortex remembers. The LLM summarizes what Cortex remembers. Neither replaces the other. The programmer moves between them fluidly — asking the model to persist what it just told her, asking it to reason about what was persisted a month ago, asking it to reconcile when new and old disagree.

The book stays a scheme-book. Cortex is where per-user, per-project facts live; the book is where the durable teaching lives. Together they are the retrieval surface the small model consults when he does not remember. He remembers the verbs; he consults Cortex and the book for the facts.

## When the LLM should not touch Cortex

Three cases where a well-behaved model refuses to compose:

  1. **Cortex is empty.** No records for the queried key. The model must not fabricate a value. Return #f or a not-found record and let the caller ask the user.
  2. **Cortex has one record, but it is stale.** The record has a :ts field older than a session-appropriate threshold. The model surfaces the age and asks whether to trust it.
  3. **Cortex has two conflicting records.** The model does not silently pick one. It surfaces the conflict as a critique record. The programmer resolves.

The general rule: the LLM never invents a Cortex fact, never picks a winner in a conflict, and never treats staleness as absence. All three are first-class outcomes with named shapes. Every combination in this appendix respects these.

For the LLM x Introspection pair, see Appendix J. For the meta-question of what the model can and cannot be expected to remember (which is really a question about what needs to be in weights versus what needs to be in Cortex versus what needs to be in the book), see Appendix N."

  :status "authored-2026-07-17"
  :closes-with "See Appendix L next.")
